<DOC><DOCNO> AP891125-0104 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 1804EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-25 0393</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0406</SECOND><HEAD>Winter-Like Storm Developing Along West Coast</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A wintry storm came ashore on the northern Pacific Coast onSaturday, threatening up to 3 feet of snow in the mountains, andstorm watches were posted all the way to the Rockies.   Rain fell at lower elevations. Snow began falling on the coastalmountain ranges of Washington, Oregon and Northern California.   Two to 3 feet of snow was possible in the northern Sierra Nevadarange in California, the National Weather Service said.   ``Travel across the Sierra should be avoided if at all possibleduring this storm,'' the weather service warned.   The weather was welcomed by ski resort operators in the Sierra,who have had a poor season so far.   ``It couldn't be better,'' said Doug Garver, manager at BorealSki Area. He said snow started falling there Thursday and ``hasn'tstopped since.''   Four to 8 inches of snow was expected by Sunday morning in southcentral Oregon, the weather service said.   Farther inland, winter storm watches were posted through Sundayfor the mountains of Utah and Utah's northern valleys, themountains of southern Idaho and southern Montana, western Wyomingand the Colorado Rockies.   From Friday night into Saturday, snow fell across the ColoradoRockies, with up to 12 inches at Gothic, 10 inches at Berthoud Passand 9 inches at Mary Jane and Steamboat, the weather service said.   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms drenched the Florida Keys.Key West was soaked with 2.30 inches of rain late Friday and got anadditional 3.25 inches during the six hours up to 1 p.m. EST.   A few showers and thunderstorms spread along the central GulfCoast.   A few light showers developed along a cold front over Iowa andeastern Nebraska. In the Northeast, light snow showers extendedover northern New England and upstate New York.   Temperatures remained in the 50s overnight in SouthernCalifornia and southern Arizona. The morning low of 55 degrees atRiverside, Calif., was the city's warmest on record for the date.   At the other extreme, lows were in the teens in northernMinnesota and Upper Michigan, and across much of the Northeast,with temperatures in single digits in northern Maine. Allentown,Pa., tied its record low for the date of 16 degrees.   The low for the Lower 48 states was 1 degree above zero atHoulton, Maine.</TEXT></DOC>